# CONSULT-45 — Architecture & Fix-Design Ranking (Opus angle)

Scope: design and RANK the candidate fixes for the cantina zone-in jerk by value vs risk vs
effort, reasoning about the main-thread frame budget and D3D9 device thread-affinity. Grounded in
the engine's actual threading model (file:line below). I do NOT re-trace sync-vs-async loading,
the GPU-resource file:line detail, or the allocator/STL/paging lateral angle — those are other
crew members.

================================================================================
1. GROUND TRUTH — the engine's threading model (what CAN move off-thread)
================================================================================

These are the load-bearing facts my ranking rests on. All verified in-tree.

**(G1) The device-affine boundary is already a clean handoff at the bytecode line.**
In `Direct3d9_VertexShaderData.cpp`:
  - `D3DCompile(...)` at **:684** — pure CPU, thread-safe, produces an `ID3DBlob` of bytecode.
    This is the EXPENSIVE part (~44 compiles on first cantina; fxc optimizer dominates).
  - `CreateVertexShader(bytecode)` at **:584** (cache-hit path) — the device-affine call. It is
    cheap (driver just registers bytecode); it MUST stay on the render/device thread.
  The two are ALREADY separated by an owned `std::vector<uint8>` of bytecode. The architecture is
  pre-shaped for "compile anywhere, create on device thread." This is the single most important
  structural fact for option 3.

**(G2) The bytecode cache key is already the permutation tuple.**
`buildByteCodeCacheKey(fileName, textureCoordinateSetKey, target)` at **:151** keys on exactly the
three inputs that determine the bytecode — and the comment says it "Mirrors
Direct3d11_ShaderCache::hashSource's contract." The `textureCoordinateSetKey` permutation IS
captured in the key. So a disk cache does NOT need to enumerate permutations offline — it lazily
accumulates whatever permutations the game actually touches, keyed correctly. (This neutralizes
the stated objection to option 2 by routing around it.)

**(G3) D3D11 ALREADY HAS the disk-persisted cache. gl05 does not.**
`Direct3d11_ShaderCache.cpp`: `ms_cacheDir`, `<cacheDir>/<hash:016x>.cso`, `tryLoad()` (:176
fopen "rb"), `store()` (:236 fopen "wb"), `install(cacheDir)` with `create_directories`. The blob
is treated as opaque & self-versioning. **The D3D9 in-memory cache (commit ff02a367e) is a
half-port of this.** Finishing it to disk is a *mirror-gl11* job — the lowest-novelty, most
de-risked kind of change this project does (cf. Phase 34 "pure mechanical gl05 mirror, ZERO
fix-what-breaks").

**(G4) The engine has a real, proven worker-thread runtime — but it deliberately does NOT do
GPU work off-thread.**
  - `runNamedThread(...)` + `Thread` priority levels (kIdle..kCritical):
    `sharedThread/src/win32/Thread.cpp`.
  - `AsynchronousLoader` (`sharedFile/AsynchronousLoader.cpp`) is a producer/consumer worker
    (`threadRoutine` :429) that ONLY pulls raw file bytes into the TreeFile cache. Resource
    construction happens back on the MAIN thread in `processCallbacks()` at **:631**
    (`(*request->callback)(request->data)`), under a per-frame budget
    `getAsynchronousLoaderCallbacksPerFrame()` (:589). It even self-throttles via an 8 MB
    `cms_postponeThreshold` (:117) so the worker never runs the cache too far ahead.
  - `FileStreamerThread` (kHigh priority, :59) is the disk-read thread; multi-priority queues
    (AudioVideo > Data > Low) with read chunking at 128 KB (`cms_maxReadSize`).
  **Conclusion:** the original SOE architecture is "stream BYTES async, build RESOURCES on the main
  thread under a callback budget." It was designed around D3D9 device affinity. Any async-compile
  design must respect that grain: move D3DCompile (CPU) off-thread, keep CreateVertexShader on the
  device thread. The infrastructure to do this (named worker threads, mutex, semaphore, the
  per-frame callback drain) ALREADY EXISTS and is battle-tested.

================================================================================
2. FRAME-BUDGET REASONING — why the jerk happens and what each fix buys
================================================================================

The hitch is a main-thread *time* stall (GIVEN: not OOM, Debug worse). At zone-in the main thread
serially does, in one or a few frames: stream/parse assets -> build appearances -> **for each new
shader permutation: HLSL rewrite + D3DCompile (fxc optimize) + CreateVertexShader** -> create
VB/IB/textures. ~44 first-load VS compiles, each tens of ms in Debug, land in a tight window. The
frame can't Present until that frame's slice of work finishes, so dt balloons and the camera
lurches (option 5 only masks the lurch, not the stall).

Two independent levers:
  - **(L1) Eliminate the work** (don't compile at all after the first ever run): disk cache.
    First-EVER load still pays once; every subsequent first-load-per-process is free.
  - **(L2) Hide the work** (compile off the main thread): async compile. First-ever load also
    smooths, because the stall moves to a worker; the main thread just waits for bytecode (or
    renders a fallback until ready).
These are COMPLEMENTARY, not competing. The optimal end state is L1+L2: disk cache makes the
steady state free; async compile smooths the genuine cold-cache first run and any
cache-invalidation event (driver/toolchain change → .cso miss).

================================================================================
3. RANKED PLAN (best value-to-risk first)
================================================================================

### #1 — Disk-persisted VS bytecode cache (mirror Direct3d11_ShaderCache to gl05) ★ FIRST STEP
- **Impact:** HIGH on the *recurring* complaint, MODERATE on a literal first-ever boot. After one
  warm run the ~44 first-cantina compiles drop to ~44 file reads + CreateVertexShader (cheap).
  This is the bulk of the felt jerk in normal play/testing.
- **Risk:** LOW. The pattern is already shipping in gl11 (G3). Blob is opaque/self-versioning;
  worst case of a stale/corrupt .cso is a `tryLoad` miss → recompile (already the current
  behavior). Key correctness is solved (G2). No threading touched → no new race surface.
- **Effort:** LOW–MEDIUM. Port `install(cacheDir)`/`tryLoad`/`store` from gl11; wire the two
  existing cache touch-points (:579 lookup, :711 fill) to also hit disk; call `install` from the
  D3D9 device-init alongside the gl11 call site. Pick a cacheDir under the writable user/stage
  dir (NOT inside a TRE). Reuse the existing key string as the filename stem (hash it for FS
  safety, same as gl11's `%016x`).
- **Key constraint:** cacheDir must be WRITABLE and per-toolchain-stable. Invalidate on a version
  stamp (toolchain/d3dcompiler version + a format byte) so a recompiled engine doesn't load
  bytecode from an incompatible fxc — gl11 already treats the blob as self-versioning; carry a
  cheap header tag to be safe.
- **Why first:** highest value-to-risk by a wide margin — it reuses a proven in-repo
  implementation, touches no thread-affinity rules, and directly kills the dominant cost on every
  load after the first. It is also a prerequisite that makes #3 mostly unnecessary in steady
  state (you only async-compile on a genuine miss).

### #2 — Async / background SHADER COMPILE (move D3DCompile off the main thread; keep
###       CreateVertexShader on the device thread)
- **Impact:** HIGH, and uniquely covers the case the disk cache can't: the genuine first-ever /
  cold-cache load and any post-invalidation miss. Smooths the stall instead of just relocating
  it.
- **Risk:** MEDIUM. This is real concurrency. But the design is constrained and safe BECAUSE of
  G1: only the pure-CPU `D3DCompile` (:684) crosses to a worker; the returned bytecode is handed
  back and `CreateVertexShader` (:584) runs on the device thread inside the existing per-frame
  drain (model it on `processCallbacks` :631). The render path must tolerate "bytecode not ready
  yet" — use a fallback/last-known VS or briefly skip the draw, exactly the kind of per-frame
  budgeted completion the AsynchronousLoader already does. Hazards to control: the `ms_defines` /
  `ms_scratchBuffer` static scratch state (:599, file-static) is NOT thread-safe — the worker must
  build its own define list, not share the statics; and the in-memory `ms_byteCodeCache` map
  (:144) needs a mutex once a worker writes it.
- **Effort:** MEDIUM–HIGH. New compile-request queue + worker (reuse `runNamedThread` and the
  Mutex/Semaphore already used by AsynchronousLoader), a "pending compile" state on the shader
  object, and a main-thread completion drain that calls CreateVertexShader. De-static the scratch
  build.
- **Key constraint:** D3D9 device affinity — NEVER call CreateVertexShader (or any device
  Create*) off the worker. Compile→bytecode off-thread; create on-thread. Also: don't async the
  //asm `D3DXAssembleShader` path (it's flat in the A/B and lives behind the FP-SEH guard).
- **Sequencing:** do this AFTER #1. With the disk cache in place, async compile only fires on
  cold misses, so its complexity is exercised rarely and its payoff (smoothing the first-ever
  load) is the only gap left.

### #3 — Offline / build-time shader precompile (what retail/SWGEmu ship)
- **Impact:** HIGH in principle (zero runtime compile, like retail) BUT…
- **Risk:** MEDIUM–HIGH on completeness. Our VS are parameterized by the runtime
  `textureCoordinateSetKey` permutation (:577, :604). Enumerating ALL permutations offline is a
  combinatorial guess; miss one and you silently fall back to runtime compile (the jerk returns
  for that asset) or worse, ship a wrong permutation. You'd need a capture-the-keys harness
  (record every (file,key,target) the game requests across content) to seed the build — which is
  essentially what the **disk cache produces for free at runtime** (G2).
- **Effort:** HIGH (new build step + permutation enumeration + packaging + a fallback path you
  still have to keep).
- **Verdict:** LOWER priority. The disk cache (#1) is a *self-populating, always-correct* superset
  of what offline precompile tries to do, without the enumeration risk. Reach for offline
  precompile only if you later want a shippable warm cache out-of-box (you could even ship the
  accumulated .cso set from a dev warm run as the "prebuilt" cache — best of both, near-zero extra
  code). So: subsumed by #1; revisit only for distribution.

### #4 — Allocator swap (faster small/large-object allocator)
- **Impact:** LOW–MODERATE on THIS hitch, and indirect. The stall is dominated by fxc
  compile time, not allocation (GIVEN E: custom free-list-tree allocator in the hot path, but the
  jerk is compile-bound). Allocation cost rides along (each compile churns transient heap) but
  killing the compiles (#1/#2) removes most of that churn anyway. Debug-worse is consistent with
  compiler/codegen + guard overhead, not primarily allocator throughput.
- **Risk:** MEDIUM–HIGH and broad. Swapping the SOE MemoryManager (or interposing
  mimalloc/rpmalloc) is a global, invasive change with its own ABI/init-order/exit-chain hazards
  and can perturb unrelated subsystems. High blast radius for a second-order win.
- **Effort:** MEDIUM–HIGH (interpose vs replace; the engine's MemoryManager has its own
  new/delete plumbing and debug instrumentation).
- **Verdict:** DEFER. Do not chase it for the zone-in jerk. Reconsider only as a separate,
  measured perf workstream AFTER #1/#2, and only if profiling then shows allocation as a real
  residual cost. (Cross-check with the lateral crew member's allocator findings before acting.)

### #5 — elapsedTime clamp (bound the VISIBLE lurch)
- **Impact:** COSMETIC only — does not reduce the stall, but caps the dt fed to camera/movement so
  a 200 ms frame doesn't teleport the view. Cheap insurance that improves *perceived* smoothness
  during any unavoidable hitch (incl. the first-ever cold load before #1 is warm, and #2's
  fallback frames).
- **Risk:** LOW, but with a correctness caveat: clamping dt makes the sim under-advance during the
  stall (movement/animation briefly lag real time). For a client where movement is server-driven
  and dt-scaled (GIVEN D), a modest clamp (e.g. cap frame dt at ~100 ms) is standard and benign;
  do NOT clamp so hard you desync from the server's authoritative position.
- **Effort:** LOW (one clamp at the frame-time source).
- **Verdict:** Ship it as a cheap COMPLEMENT, not a fix. Pair it with #1. It's the only item that
  helps the literal first-ever boot before any cache is warm, and it costs almost nothing.

================================================================================
4. RECOMMENDED SEQUENCE
================================================================================

  Step 0 (free, parallel): add the elapsedTime clamp (#5) — bounds the lurch immediately, helps
          even the cold first run, near-zero risk/effort.
  Step 1 (THE first real fix): disk-persisted VS bytecode cache (#1) — mirror gl11's
          Direct3d11_ShaderCache into gl05. Highest value-to-risk; reuses shipping code; kills the
          recurring jerk after one warm run.
  Step 2 (if cold-load smoothness still matters): async compile (#2) — move D3DCompile to a worker
          using the existing thread infra, keep CreateVertexShader on the device thread. Now only
          fires on genuine cache misses, so its concurrency risk is rarely exercised.
  Skip/defer: offline precompile (#3, subsumed by #1 — optionally ship #1's warm .cso set as the
          "prebuilt" cache later); allocator swap (#4, separate measured workstream, not for this
          bug).

**Single highest value-to-risk FIRST step: the disk-persisted VS bytecode cache (#1)** — it is a
mechanical mirror of an already-shipping gl11 component (Direct3d11_ShaderCache), reuses the
existing, already-correct permutation key, touches NO thread-affinity rules, and directly
eliminates the dominant compile cost on every load after the first.

